Mobile operator MTN has published its integrated annual report for 2018, revealing what the company’s top executives earned in the last financial year. MTN Group posted a solid set of results for the full year 2018 including a 10.7% jump in service revenue for the year, while revenue climbed 6% to R134.56 billion. Service revenue in MTN Nigeria grew 172%, MTN Ghana was up 23%, and MTN South Africa was up 4.2%. Voice revenues grew 7.3% to R82.2 billion, data was up 22% to R28.5 billion, fintech grew 46.8% to R7.8 billion, but digital declined 32.9% to R3.9 billion. Enterprise and wholesale grew by 8.4% and 63.7% respectively to R13.4 billion and R2.8 billion – and operating profit climbed to R23.6 billion, from R20.6 billion before. The group paid its top two executives a total of R65.46 million for the year, with other prescribed officers taking a combined R176.96 million for a total of R242.4 million. Group CEO, Rob Shuter earned R42.92 million, including a basic salary of R15.28 million and bonuses and other benefits exceeding R26 million. Chief financial officer Ralph Mupita earned R22.54 million, while MTN SA chief executive Godfrey Motsa took home R23.5 million. This is how much MTN’s executives were paid: <img class="aligncenter wp-image-307798" src="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/CEO-CFO.png" alt="" width="898" height="381" srcset="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/CEO-CFO.png 1980w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/CEO-CFO-300x127.png 300w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/CEO-CFO-768x326.png 768w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/CEO-CFO-1024x434.png 1024w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/CEO-CFO-1200x509.png 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px" /> <img class="aligncenter wp-image-307800" src="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads